ons, celebrating their efforts to limit individual freedoms and property in pursuit of economic recovery and social peace. By tracing the movement of people and ideas across the South Atlantic, Teixeira vividly shows how two countries not often studied for their economic creativity became major centers for policy experimentation. Portuguese and Brazilian officials created laws and agencies to control pricing and production, which in turn generated new social frictions and economic problems, as individuals and firms tried to evade the rules. And yet, Teixeira argues, despite the failings and frustrations of Brazil’s and Portugal’s corporatist experiments, the ideas and institutions tested in the 1930s and 1940s constituted a new legal and technical tool kit for the rise of economic planning, shaping how governments regulate labor and market relations to the present day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh  aA Third Path: Corporatism in Brazil and Portugal.  aEstado Novo Brazil.  aEstado Novo Portugal.  aGreat Depression.  aMelissa Teixeira.  aPolitical economy.  aWorld War II.  aauthoritarianism.  abooks.  aconstitutionalism.  adictatorship, fascism.  aeconomic crisis.  aeconomic development.  aeconomic planning.  ahistory of economic ideas.  ainternational relations.  aliberalism.  astate-directed development.  awartime economic planning.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691258157?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691258157423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691258157/original  a978-3-11-074975-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB 